{
  "doc_id": "42625",
  "text": "In recent years evidence has been accumulating to indicate that certain inert or noble gases, existing as mono-atomic gases with low chemical reactivity, nevertheless express biological activity. Numerous in vitro and in vivo experiments have demonstrated intriguing biological effects for xenon, argon and helium, with neuro-and organo-protective properties as the most clinically promising [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Extensive research has further revealed some of the underlying mechanisms and include competitive antagonism at the NMDA/AMPA receptor [CITATION_3] , anti-apoptotic properties (inhibition of mitochondrial cytochrome c release) [CITATION_4] , activation of pro-survival signaling pathways (increased expression of Bcl-2/Bcl-xL, inhibition of Bax) [CITATION_5] , MAPK regulation (p38, ERK 1/2 ) [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] and potassium ion channels activation (K ATP , TREK-1) [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . The preclinical models suggest potential clinical benefit in indications such as traumatic brain injury, ischemic or hemorrhagic stroke, perinatal hypoxic-ischemic brain injury, coronary artery bypass graft surgery, organ protection during transplantation, chronic pain, and addiction [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] . Any clinical benefit, however, would require chronic (or repetitive) administration of inert gases, in contrast to the currently accepted acute, single administration for the induction and maintenance of general anesthesia (e.g. xenon).",
